    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="534"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d534">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/1027</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 16, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your telegram March 27.<note n="2" xml:id="d534fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_356">p. 356</ref>.</note>
                    Department presumes prize-claims committee will consider only claims growing out
                    of detention of ships and cargoes which have actually come within jurisdiction
                    prize <pb facs="0629" n="371" xml:id="pg_371"/> court and not claims growing out
                    detentions of vessels and cargoes in cases where writs of prize court have not
                    been issued. Adjudication of claims by a committee seems to supplant remedy
                    pointed out in British note of February 10, 1915, to Ambassador, regarding suits
                    for damages in prize court in accordance with Order V, rule 2, British prize
                    court rules. Endeavor obtain full information regarding these matters. Report by
                    telegraph.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
